  <h2>Rosacea</h2>
 <p>
Rosacea is a common face rash with adults.  Rosacea has three stages. In the first stage the face becomes red.  With time, small blood vessels develop making the redness more noticeable.  Many times in the first stage the skin can feel similar to a mild sunburn with the simple actions of smiling, frowning, or squinting.  In the second stage of rosacea, the redness covers a larger area of the face and slight swelling, along with pimples, and pustules develop. This is especially noticeable on the nose, mid-forehead, and chin. As the condition progresses, prominent facial pores can develop.  The third stage is characterized by swelling and growth of the nose and central facial areas. At times the ears may be involved as well. This can be very disfiguring. This stage is known as rhinophyma. Most patients do not progress to the third stage of rosacea.<br><br>

Common treatments include antibiotics such as MetroGel, MetroCream and sulfur preparations applied to the skin one to two times a day.  These treatments work well for many people with rosacea.
Retin-A is also an effective treatment and can decrease the small blood vessels.
 
